<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900621-0032</DOCNO><DOCID>900621-0032.</DOCID><HL>   House Rules Panel Set   Flag Bill Vote for Today</HL><DATE>06/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><IN>LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)</IN><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Democratic majority on the House RulesCommittee sent the flag-desecration amendment to the Housefloor for a vote today despite particularly savage demands byRepublicans to wait until next week.   The GOP wanted to use the weekend to round up votes forthe proposed constitutional amendment, but Speaker ThomasFoley (D., Wash.) pushed for bringing it to the floorquickly. The vote is expected to be close.</LP><TEXT>   During debate on the floor, Rep. Gerald Solomon (R., N.Y.)accused Mr. Foley of &quot;kowtowing to the ilk like the CommunistYouth Brigade to allow them to trample and desecrate ourAmerican flag.&quot; His remarks were challenged as improper byRep. Barbara Boxer (D., Calif.), and he was forced towithdraw them after a ruling by Speaker Pro Tempore JoleneUnsoeld (D., Wash.) that they violated House rules concerningproper debate.   The House Judiciary Committee voted 19-17 Tuesday to sendthe amendment to the floor without recommendation. The RulesCommittee, 9-4, set the vote for today, waiving the normalthree-day waiting period.   Speaker Foley said there was no reason to delay themeasure, which he said had been &quot;debated and discussed asmuch as any other legislative proposal of this Congress.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>